%N A389232 Total number of decreasing runs in all heapable permutations of length n.
%C A389232 A permutation of [1..n] is heapable if it can be inserted, one element at a time, into a binary min-heap without violating the heap property.
%C A389232 A decreasing run in a permutation is a maximal contiguous subsequence that is strictly decreasing. For example, in the permutation (3,1,4,2) the decreasing runs are (3,1) and (4,2).
%H A389232 Manolopoulos Panagiotis, <a href="/A389232/a389232.py.txt">Python program</a>.
%H A389232 Benjamin Chen, Michael Cho, Mario Tutuncu-Macias, and Tony Tzolov, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dam.2023.01.025">Efficient methods of calculating the number of heapable permutations</a>, Discrete Applied Mathematics Volume 331, 31 May 2023, Pages 126-137.
%e A389232 For n=4, the heapable permutations are:
%e A389232   (1,2,3,4): runs (1),(2),(3),(4) => 4 decreasing runs.
%e A389232   (1,3,2,4): runs (1), (3,2), (4) => 3 decreasing runs.
%e A389232   (1,2,4,3): runs (1),(2), (4,3) => 3 decreasing runs.
%e A389232   (1,4,2,3): runs (1), (4,2), (3) => 3 decreasing runs.
%e A389232   (1,3,4,2): runs (1),(3),(4,2) => 3 decreasing run.
%e A389232 So among the 5 heapable permutations of length 4:
%e A389232   1 permutations have 4 decreasing run,
%e A389232   4 permutations have 3 decreasing runs,
%e A389232   for a total of 16 decreasing runs.
